Hi! Thanks so much for maintaining this project. It would be great to have a function to simultaneously map and filter a collection. That is, to map a collection of values to another collection of values, but to exclude a result if the mapping function returns falsy or `null`.

For instance, we could take a set of years, and return the current age of people born before the current year, dropping the years in the future:

```js
const years = [1942, 1978, 2000, 2021, 2022, 2030, 2045];
const currentYear = 2021;
const ages  = filterMap(years, year => year <= currentYear ? currentYear - year : null)
// => [79, 43, 21, 0]
```

A similar feature already exists in [Rust](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/iter/trait.Iterator.html#method.filter_map), and I've found it to be quite useful.

Example:

```js
const items = [
  { id: 21, second: 1 },
  { id: 1, second: 2 },
  { id: 3, second: 3 }
];
 
_.sortBy(items, i => [i.id, i.second]);
```

Result:

`[Object {id: 1, second: 2}, Object {id: 21, second: 1}, Object {id: 3, second: 3}]`

This seems to happen when using a projection function to get the keys; it appears to convert to strings and do an alphanumeric sort behind the scenes (thus '21' sorts before '1').
